description: {"blocks":[{"key":"frse8","text":"We have modified the Cleavage Under Targets and Release Using Nuclease (CUT\u0026RUN) method for epigenomic profiling of histone modifications and chromatin proteins to use dissected Drosophila tissues. In CUT\u0026RUN, cells or tissues are permeabilized and incubated under conditions where a factor-specific antibody can bind at sites of a chromatin protein. This antibody is then used to tether a protein A-micrococcal nuclease fusion protein, which upon activation releases specific protein-DNA complexes into the supernatant for paired-end DNA sequencing, and leaving the vast majority of DNA behind in the cellular pellet. CUT\u0026RUN outperforms the most widely used Chromatin Immunoprecipitation (ChIP) protocols in resolution, signal-to-noise, and depth of sequencing required. Previous versions of CUT\u0026RUN have used isolated nuclei, mammalian cultured cells, or yeast spheroplasts. Here we have modified the CUT\u0026RUN protocol to manipulate imaginal discs and tissues dissected from larvae with magnetic beads without isolation of cells or nuclei. About 10 imaginal discs provides high-quality data for a histone modification or for a chromatin factor. A simple spike-in strategy is used for accurate quantitation of experiment yields and library preparation. From larvae to purified DNA, CUT\u0026RUN requires 1-2 days with minimal handling after dissection.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}
guidelines:
{"blocks":[{"key":"5pl5e","text":"The strategy of this protocol is to coat dissected Drosophila imaginal discs or tissues with ConA magnetic beads, and perform all washes and buffer changes by magnetic capture of the sample. This method uses small numbers of imaginal discs, and uses digitonin to gently permeabilize the unfixed tissues. Finally, the protocol uses Ampure beads to efficiently recover DNA, avoiding the risk of contamination by phenol or chloroform. Bottles where larvae are not too dense provide well-fed crawling larvae that are easiest to dissect and provide the most tissue.","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2c5b5","text":"","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2e62o","text":"The protocol workflow is as follows:
   
Day 1: Larvae to primary antibody incubation
Preparing working solutions and conA beads (Steps 1-4, 15')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":36},{"style":"italic","offset":41,"length":45}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"e32c2","text":"Dissecting larvae (Steps 5-6, 15')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"5k1fn","text":"Binding tissues to beads (Step 7, 10')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3l786","text":"Binding primary antibody (Steps 8-10, O/N)","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"19q56","text":"","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"682mp","text":"Day 2: primary antibody incubation to DNA recovery","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":50}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"cu3m7","text":"Binding primary antibody (Steps 11-12, 10')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9dvfd","text":"Optional: binding secondary antibody (Steps 13-16, 1 hr 15')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"fied1","text":"nuclease tethering (Steps 17-20, 1 hr 20')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ceoma","text":"DNA cleavage (Steps 21-25,  1 hr 5')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3e7o7","text":"DNA recovery (Steps 26-36, 3 hrs 30')","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1leg6","text":"   
Preparing Libraries, sequencing, data processing and analysis is performed as perviously described for CUT&RUN protocols (eg. Skene et al (2018). Targeted in situ genome-wide profiling with high efficiency for low cell numbers. Nature Protocols 13:1006-1019. doi: 10.1038/nprot.2018.015.","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"apcaj","text":"","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"atuf8","text":"Limitations","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"b0d3b","text":"The success of CUT&RUN depends on the affinity of an antibody for its target and its specificity under the conditions used for binding. Because antibodies bind to their epitopes in the solid state using CUT&RUN, we expect that antibodies successfully tested for specificity by immunofluorescence (IF) will be likely to work with CUT&RUN, with the caveat that IF generally involves fixation, whereas formaldehyde fixation decreases the efficiency of CUT&RUN.","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"cs3j4","text":" ","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"97vis","text":"One of the limitations of working with small amounts of tissues is that the amount of DNA recovered can be very low, such that analysis even by sensitive capillary electrophoresis or picogreen assays (e.g. Agilent Tapestation and Qubit) are problematic. In addition, high resolution mapping techniques that cleave a minimal footprint are not suitable to PCR-based analysis of known binding loci, as it is not commonly possible to design ~50 bp PCR amplicons. As such, we recommend using a positive control antibody that targets an abundant epitope and therefore the DNA can be readily detected. We have successfully used a rabbit monoclonal antibody raised against the H3K27me3 histone modification, with capillary electrophoresis showing with the amount of cleaved fragments being proportional to the number of starting cells. A nucleosomal ladder is expected by Tapestation or other sensitive electrophoretic analysis method, and the use of a monoclonal antibody avoids potential lot-to-lot variation that can complicate troubleshooting. For less abundant epitopes such as trnascription factors, we often do not detect any cleaved fragments by Tapestation, yet successful libraries can be prepared from these reactions. As a negative control, we recommend the use of a non-specific rabbit IgG antibody that will randomly coat the chromatin at low density without sequence bias. We do not recommend a no-antibody control, as the lack of tethering increases the possibility that any slight carry-over of pA-MN will result in preferential fragmentation of hyper-accessible DNA. We recommend activating the nuclease for 30 minutes as a starting point that can be tailored based upon epitope abundance and antibody concentration.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3d28u","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6g55e","text":"In the standard CUT&RUN protocol we recommend allowing the cleaved chromatin complexes to diffuse out of the nuclei, thereby permitting simple isolation of the cut DNA from the supernatant fraction with the undigested genome retained in the intact nuclei. In such cases, DNA extraction and size-selection of fragments below ~700 bp can be used for profiling.","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

materials.name: Negative control antibody to an absent epitope, e.g. guinea pig α-rabbit antibody
Protein A–Micrococcal Nuclease (pA-MNase) fusion protein (provided in 50% glycerol by the authors upon request). Store at -20 oC.
Spike-in DNA (e.g., from Saccharomyces cerevisiae micrococcal nuclease-treated chromatin, provided by authors upon request)
Distilled, deionized or RNAse-free H2O (dH2O e.g., Promega, cat. no. P1197)
RNase A, DNase and protease-free (10 mg/ml)
Rabbit IgG antibody to a chromatin protein of interest. A mouse IgG antibody can be used with indirect tethering.
yeast spike-in DNA (1 ng/mL). NOTE: this fragmented to ~150 bp by MNase digestion of yeast nuclei and resuspended in water at 1 ng/mL.

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"btjgf","text":"Prepare a fresh 5% digitonin solution as follows:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":16,"length":12}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ao52v","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"euatj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6lnjv","text":"Weigh out 50 mg digitonin powder in a 2 ml microcentrifuge tube. Boil some water in a small beaker in a microwave oven, and pipette in and out to warm the 1000 μL pipette tip. Pipette the hot water into the tube with the digitonin powder, close the cap, and quickly vortex on full until the digitonin is completely dissolved. If refrigerated, this stock can be used within a week, but will need reheating as the digitonin slowly precipitates. The effectiveness of digitonin varies between batches, so testing permeability of Trypan blue is recommended to determine effective concentrations. We have obtained excellent results with 0.02-0.1% digitonin.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"safety","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":[],"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"9ar4r","text":"• CAUTION: Digitonin is toxic and care should be taken especially when weighing out the powder. ","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"dcsqc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5licn","text":"Prepare Dig-Block-EDTA (dbe+) Buffer (25 mL):","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":8,"length":28}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"b40fg","text":"Add 25 mL of Wash+ Buffer to a 50 mL conical tube","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"67ab4","text":"Add 100 µL 0.5 M EDTA                       final 2 mM","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2u0of","text":"Add 250 µL 5% Digitonin                     final 0.05%","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3b4q7","text":"Keep on ice or store overnight at 4˚C.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"fkvcr","text":"Prepare ConA beads:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":8,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"508pa","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9scp4","text":"Gently vortex bottle of Bio-Mag Plus Concanavalin A-coated beads. Transfer 150 µL of ConA bead slurry to an eppendorf. Grab beads with a magnet for 5’, remove buffer and replace with 1 mL Binding buffer. Incubate 1’. Wash 2X. Resuspend ConA beads in 150 µL of Binding buffer. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"e9r1e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"66gdp","text":"Collect healthy 3rd instar larvae in a glass dish with PBT. Wash off any yeast and food.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f1ls7","text":"OVERNIGHT","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4okpj","text":"Aliquot 200 µL Wash+ buffer into 2 wells of a clean shallow dissection dish for each sample. Pick up larvae and transfer to the dissection dish, and dissect out 10 wing discs. Aim to take less than 10 minutes, so that discs remain healthy. Use a 200 µL pipette tip to transfer the wing discs to the second well of Wash+ buffer.\n","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6tqfm","text":"Add 15 µL ConA bead suspension to an eppendorf. Use a 200 µL pipette tip to transfer the wing discs to the eppendorf with a minimal volume of Wash+ buffer. Mix by gentle pipetting. Incubate 10' RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"d0omk","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2elvu","text":"All successive buffer changes are by grabbing beads with the magnet, pipetting off liquid, and replacing with new buffers. Be careful not to withdraw any beads during washes.\n","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":175}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bcmk1","text":"Block the tissues: Add 1 mL dbe+ buffer to each eppendorf. Gently flick the tube to mix, and incubate 10’ at RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cf5gi","text":"Prepare antibody dilutions in dbe+ buffer. You’ll need 100 µL for each sample, typically at 1:100 dilution.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"iokh","text":"For example, you are doing 10 reactions with 1 antibody. Aliquot 1 mL dbe+ buffer, add 10 µL 1˚ antibody, and pipette to mix. If you are doing 10 different antibodies, aliquot 100 µL dbe+, add 1 µL 1˚ antibody and mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"e4ppt","text":"Place eppendorfs on magnet, and let bind for 2’. Pipette off the buffer, and replace with 100 µL antibody dilution. Incubate eppendorfs at a 60˚ angle on an orbital shaker, orbiting slowly, 4˚C O/N.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"e61jb","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"csu5k","text":"\n","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"57ghl","text":"Very briefly spin tubes to collect liquid if necessary. Place tubes on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and replace with 500 µL dbe+ buffer to wash the beads. Resuspend sample by pipetting and incubate 2’ RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d22l7","text":"Repeat Wash. Very briefly spin tubes to collect liquid if necessary. Place tubes on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and replace with 500 µL dbe+ buffer to wash the beads. Resuspend sample by pipetting and incubate 2’ RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7pto","text":"This section uses a secondary antibody to adapt mouse IgG primary antibody for protein-A binding. If not needed, skip to Step 17.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":129}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"f81qr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9h6qr","text":"Prepare secondary rabbit anti-mouse IgG antibody dilution in dbe+ buffer. You’ll need 100 µL for each sample at 1:100 dilution. For 10 reactions with a mouse primary antibody, aliquot 1 mL dbe+ buffer, add 10 µL 1˚ antibody, and pipette to mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"857hh","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"fthip","text":"Place sample eppendorfs on magnet, and let bind for 2’. Pipette off the buffer, and replace with 100 µL secondary antibody dilution. Incubate eppendorfs at a 60˚ angle on an orbital shaker, orbiting slowly, 1 hr at RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dt0ah","text":"Very briefly spin tubes to collect liquid if necessary. Place tubes on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and replace with 500 µL dbe+ buffer to wash the beads. Resuspend sample by pipetting and incubate 2’ RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c76lm","text":"Repeat Wash. Very briefly spin tubes to collect liquid if necessary. Place tubes on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and replace with 500 µL dbe+ buffer to wash the beads. Resuspend sample by pipetting and incubate 2’ RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6ag6b","text":"Dilution of different batches of pAMN are calibrated. This step uses Batch #6, which is used at a 1:400 dilution. Use the appropriate calibrated dilution of other batches.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":171}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9vmjb","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ds28p","text":"Prepare pAMN dilution: Aliquot 1 mL dbe+ buffer, add 2.5 µl pAMN#6 and mix by pipetting. This is enough for 10 samples.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d0ajd","text":"Place sample tubes on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and replace with 100 µL pAMN dilution. Resuspend sample by pipetting and incubate orbiting slowly 1 hr, RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5j3i4","text":"Wash: very briefly spin tubes to collect liquid if necessary. Place samples on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and replace with 500 µL Wash+ buffer. Resuspend samples by pipetting and incubate 2’.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"80nr3","text":"Repeat wash: very briefly spin tubes to collect liquid if necessary. Place samples on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and replace with 500 µL Wash+ buffer. Resuspend samples by pipetting and incubate 2’.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5j6jk","text":"Prepare Wash+C buffer: Aliquot 1.5 mL Wash+ buffer, add 30 µL 100 mM CaCl2 and mix. Place buffer on ice and chill. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sub","offset":73,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"27pgj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6ujsl","text":"Final concentration is 2 mM CaCl2.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":34},{"style":"sub","offset":32,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"7ua1t","text":"\n","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ace08","text":"Place sample tubes on magnet to grab beads, 2’. Remove buffer, and place samples on ice to chill tubes. Promptly resuspend sample with 150 µl Wash+C buffer and start timer. Incubate 30’ on ice. Occasionally flick the tube to resuspend the beads.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c4c8b","text":"Prepare 2XSTOPyR buffer: aliquot 1600 µL 2XSTOP buffer. Add 3.2 µL 1 ng/mL yeast spike-in DNA and 10 µL RNaseA. Chill on ice until cleavage reaction is complete.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"e47rp","text":"Prepare Pellet buffer: Aliquot 800 µL Wash+ buffer, add 800 µL 2XSTOP buffer. Add 3.2 µL of 1 ng/mL yeast spike-in DNA. Add 17 µL 10% SDS and 22 µL of 20mg/mL proteinase K. Store at RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6mn53","text":"At the end of 30’ incubation, add 150 µL 2XSTOPyR buffer to each sample tube and pipette to mix. Incubate samples in a 37˚C water bath, 30’.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"4992p","text":"\n","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"io79","text":"This section includes DNA recovery from both supernatant and pellet fractions. In initial experiments with a new antibody, we compare the abundance of cleaved DNA in supernatant and pellet fractions to confirm that most of the cleaved DNA is soluble. in most cases this is the case, and then library construction and sequencing is performed only with supernatant DNA.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":367}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6st5h","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"84ecb","text":"The following steps describe DNA recovery from both supernatant and pellet fractions.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":85}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bd69j","text":"Chromatin fractionation: Grab beads on magnet, 2’. Transfer the supernatant containing cleaved chromatin particles to a new tube, marked ‘sample#S’. Resuspend pellet in 150 µL Pellet buffer, add a ‘P’ to the tube label. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"5omfh","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"8s7o3","text":"The 'P' tube is a transient tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":33}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"98jim","text":"Add 2 µL 10% SDS and 2.5 µL of 20 mg /mL Proteinase K to each ‘S’ sample and mix by brief vortexing. Incubate ‘S’ and ‘P’ samples in a 50˚C water bath, 2 hr.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d929d","text":"To ‘S’ tubes: Use wide-bore green tips to add 40 µL AmpureXP bead slurry and 560 µL MXP buffer to each tube, mix thoroughly by 10X pipetting. Incubate 15’ RT. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9k57v","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ccktg","text":"This is a non-size-selective recovery of DNA fragments; the PEG:sample ratio is 2V. Total volume is ~900 µL.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":108}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"btphe","text":"To ‘P’ tubes: grab ConA beads with magnet, 2’. Transfer supernatant to a new tube. Beads are very slippery in this buffer. Incubate 15’ RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":83,"length":39}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1biks","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6r54m","text":"This is a size-selective recovery of DNA; the PEG:sample ratio is 0.7V. The fragments you are looking for will be in the supernatant!","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":158}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ftdqq","text":"To ‘P’ samples: grab Ampure beads with magnet, 5’. Beads are very slippery in this buffer. Transfer supernatant to a new tube, tag-labeled as ‘sample#PX’. Add 40 µL AmpureXP bead slurry and 155 µL MXP buffer to each tube, mix thoroughly by 10X pipetting. Incubate 15’ RT. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":51,"length":39}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"d4pf3","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ng85","text":"This is a non-size-selective recovery of DNA; the PEG:sample ratio is 2V. {"blocks":[{"key":"jnv6","text":"24) To ‘S’ and ‘PX’ tubes: grab Ampure beads with magnet, 5’. Beads are very slippery in this buffer. Pipette off buffer, making sure not to remove beads at the end.
